According to Article 68 of the EU AI Act, the scientific panel of independent experts is established to support the enforcement activities under this Regulation. The panel consists of experts selected by the Commission on the basis of up-to-date scientific or technical expertise in the field of AI necessary for the tasks set out in paragraph 3. The scientific panel shall advise and support the AI Office, in particular with regard to the following tasks:

1. Supporting the implementation and enforcement of this Regulation as regards general-purpose AI models and systems, in particular by:
(i) alerting the AI Office of possible systemic risks at Union level of general-purpose AI models, in accordance with Article 90;
(ii) contributing to the development of tools and methodologies for evaluating capabilities of general-purpose AI models and systems, including through benchmarks;
(iii) providing advice on the classification of general-purpose AI models with systemic risk;
(iv) providing advice on the classification of various general-purpose AI models and systems;
(v) contributing to the development of tools and templates;

2. Supporting the work of market surveillance authorities, at their request;

3. Supporting cross-border market surveillance activities as referred to in Article 74(11), without prejudice to the powers of market surveillance authorities;

4. Supporting the AI Office in carrying out its duties in the context of the Union safeguard procedure pursuant to Article 81.

The experts on the scientific panel shall perform their tasks with impartiality and objectivity, and shall ensure the confidentiality of information and data obtained in carrying out their tasks and activities. They shall neither seek nor take instructions from anyone when exercising their tasks under paragraph 3.

According to Article 59 of the EU AI Act, personal data lawfully collected for other purposes may be processed within the AI regulatory sandbox solely for the purpose of developing, training, and testing certain AI systems in the sandbox when the following conditions are met:

1. The AI systems shall be developed for safeguarding substantial public interest by a public authority or another natural or legal person and in one or more of the following areas:
   (i) public safety and public health, including disease detection, diagnosis prevention, control and treatment and improvement of health care systems;
   (ii) a high level of protection and improvement of the quality of the environment, protection of biodiversity, protection against pollution, green transition measures, climate change mitigation and adaptation measures;

2. The processing of personal data shall be necessary for the development, training, and testing of the AI systems;

3. The processing of personal data shall be proportionate to the aim pursued;

4. The processing of personal data shall not involve sensitive data as referred to in Article 9 of Regulation (EU) 2016/679, unless the data subject has given explicit consent or the processing is necessary for reasons of substantial public interest;

5. The processing of personal data shall be subject to appropriate safeguards, including technical and organizational measures, to ensure the protection of the rights and freedoms of the data subjects; and

6. The processing of personal data shall be subject to appropriate transparency and information obligations towards the data subjects.

According to Article 27 of the EU AI Act, when determining if an AI system qualifies as high risk, especially in relation to their potential adverse impacts, the following fundamental rights must be taken into account:

1. The right to respect for private and family life;
2. The right to the protection of personal data;
3. The right to non-discrimination;
4. The right to equal treatment and the prohibition of unfair discrimination;
5. The right to access to information and education;
6. The right to effective remedy, including to obtain human review;
7. The right to a fair trial;
8. The presumption of innocence and the right to defence;
9. The right to freedom of thought, conscience and religion;
10. The right to freedom of expression;
11. The freedom to conduct a business;
12. The right to property;
13. The right to health;
14. The right to education;
15. The right to work;
16. The right to social protection;
17. Consumer protection rights;
18. Environmental protection rights.

According to Article 58 of the EU AI Act, the implementing acts for AI regulatory sandboxes must include common principles on the following issues to ensure uniformity across the Union:

(a) eligibility and selection criteria for participation in the AI regulatory sandbox;
(b) procedures for the application, participation, monitoring, exiting from and termination of the AI regulatory sandbox, including the sandbox plan and the exit report;
(c) the terms and conditions applicable to the participants.

These implementing acts must also ensure that AI regulatory sandboxes are open to any applying provider or prospective provider of an AI system who fulfils eligibility and selection criteria, which shall be transparent and fair, and that national competent authorities inform applicants of their decision within three months of the application. Additionally, the procedures, processes, and administrative requirements for application, selection, participation, and exiting the AI regulatory sandbox must be simple, easily intelligible, and clearly communicated to facilitate the participation of SMEs, including start-ups, with limited legal and administrative capacities and are streamlined across the Union, in order to avoid fragmentation.

According to the EU AI Act, high-risk AI systems related to migration, asylum, and border control management are those that pose a high risk of harm to the health and safety or the fundamental rights of persons, taking into account both the severity of the possible harm and its probability of occurrence. These systems are specifically pre-defined in the Regulation and include:

- AI systems used for biometric identification and categorization of natural persons in public spaces;
- AI systems used to determine the likelihood of a natural person's presence in a certain location or their involvement in a committed crime;
- AI systems used to process data from social media platforms for the purpose of assessing the security or migration risk posed by natural persons;
- AI systems used to support decision-making in relation to the management of borders, asylum, and migration, including the processing of personal data for the purpose of determining the legal status of natural persons.

It is important to note that these are not the only high-risk AI systems identified in the EU AI Act, and that the Act also includes provisions for the assessment, certification, and monitoring of these systems to ensure their compliance with ethical and legal standards.

I would be happy to clarify. According to Article 53(1), point (a) of the EU AI Act, the technical documentation for providers of general-purpose AI models to downstream providers that integrate the model into their AI system must contain at least the following information:

1. A general description of the general-purpose AI model, including:
   (a) the tasks that the model is intended to perform and the type and nature of AI systems into which it can be integrated;
   (b) the acceptable use policies applicable;
   (c) the date of release and methods of distribution;
   (d) how the model interacts, or can be used to interact, with hardware or software that is not part of the model itself, where applicable;
   (e) the versions of relevant software related to the use of the general-purpose AI model, where applicable.

