According to Article 71 of the EU AI Act, the following factors may be considered in determining administrative fines for infringements:

1. The nature, gravity, and duration of the infringement;
2. The intentional or negligent character of the infringement;
3. The degree of responsibility of the infringer, taking into account technical and organizational measures implemented by them;
4. The financial benefits gained or losses avoided as a result of the infringement;
5. The harm caused to individuals or society, including the severity and scale of the potential harm;
6. The previous infringements committed by the infringer;
7. The measures taken by the infringer to mitigate the damage caused by the infringement;
8. The cooperation of the infringer with the supervisory authority to remedy the infringement and mitigate its possible adverse effects;
9. The categories of personal data affected by the infringement;
10. The manner in which the infringement became known to the supervisory authority, in particular whether the infringer reported the infringement;
11. The adherence to approved codes of conduct or approved certification mechanisms; and
12. Any other aggravating or mitigating factors applicable to the circumstances of the case.

According to Article 47 of the EU AI Act, the EU declaration of conformity must include the following details:

1. The name and address of the provider or the authorised representative established in the Union;
2. A description of the AI system, including its intended purpose and, where applicable, its operating environment;
3. The relevant harmonised standards or other technical specifications applied in full or in part, and descriptions of the methods used to address the essential requirements of this Regulation where harmonised standards or other technical specifications have not been applied;
4. The results of the conformity assessment, including the identification of the notified body, where applicable;
5. The name and address of the person authorised to sign on behalf of the provider or the authorised representative established in the Union;
6. The date of the declaration;
7. The identification of the AI system, including the serial number, batch number or any other element allowing its identification, where applicable;
8. The statement that the AI system is in conformity with the requirements of this Regulation;
9. The identification of any harmonised standards or other technical specifications not applied in full, and the reasons for not applying them;
10. The identification of any national technical rules not applied, and the reasons for not applying them;
11. The identification of any other relevant Union legislation with which the AI system complies;
12. The identification of any third-party components or sub-systems that do not comply with the requirements of this Regulation, and the reasons for their non-compliance;
13. The identification of any residual risks associated with the intended use of the AI system, and the measures taken to address them.

